            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgPlanckHistory\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPlanckHistory', '0%')\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: History of the universe according to the |Lambda-CDM model (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9",
                     "text": "©ESA – C. Carreau",
                     "page": "History of Cosmic Formation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### All Together\n\nThe image in this section represents our understanding of the history of the universe according to the Lambda-CDM model. As can be observed, after Cosmic Inflation, the process of formation of the particles we are about to study begins (<htcite0>).\n\n#### Who came first?\n\nRight after Inflation, the first particles began to appear in the universe. To understand them, let's reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9",
                     "text": "©ESA – C. Carreau",
                     "page": "History of Cosmic Formation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: The universe is like me</b><br /><br />The laws of the universe do not change over time. Thus, we can look at our own growth and, from that, propose an analogy with the development of the universe.<br /><br />We start with the union of our parents' cells and develop inside our mother, forming a baby that is born after gestation. After the baby stage, we become children; then adolescents; and finally, adults.<br /><br />Would it make sense for the universe to start with large structures already in place, like the Moon, stars, and planets?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Just as we started as small cells until we became who we are, the universe also started small.\n\n#### First Particles\n\nImmediately after the end of Inflation—which lasted less than a second—the first elementary particles began to appear (<htcite0>).\n\nAlthough particles have existed in the universe for billions of years, our discovery and understanding of them only occurred in the 20th century, according to the Gregorian calendar.\n\nThe idea of something indivisible, called the \"atom\", originated with Democritus, around <htdate0> (<htcite1>).\n\nWith advances in knowledge and the development of machines capable of making more precise measurements, we concluded that atomic models like Rutherford's (<htcite2>; <htcite3>), represented in Graph 1, considered only the electron as a fundamental particle (<htcite4>).\n\nOther particles, like protons and neutrons, contained within them even smaller particles, which we now know as quarks (<htcite5>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9",
                     "text": "©ESA – C. Carreau",
                     "page": "History of Cosmic Formation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5e2b9861-0f98-4414-ac8b-134cefa6b213",
                     "text": "Berryman, Sylvia",
                     "page": "",
